Visualize RBR pressure sensor data¶

Visualize RBR pressure sensor data QC and statistical parameters from ROXSI 2022 Asilomar Small-Scale Array measurements.

Read and plot bathymetry¶

Left plot shows raw eTrac data points of SSA bathymetry. Right plot shows interpolated bathymetry with RBRSoloD moorings marked with triangles and RBRDuetDT moorings marked with squares. Moorings without pressure sensors are marked with red crosses.

Figure

RBR wave statistics¶

Plots of spectral wave parameters ($H_\mathrm{s}$ and energy-weighted mean period $T_\mathrm{m}$) from linear surface reconstructions.

Figure

Pressure vs. temperature¶

Plot time series of 20-minute mean pressure vs. mean temperature for moorings just in front (C2; serialno. 210357), on top (C3; serialno. 210358) and behind (C4; serialno. 210359) the rock in the across-shore direction. Also include time series of $H_\mathrm{s}$ (linear reconstruction) for these locations.

Note that the central mooring (C3) is located lower down in the water column (higher pressure) than the surrounding moorings C2 and C4.

The rapid warming event on which the following figure focuses on is marked with gray shading.

Figure

Rapid warming event¶

Investigate rapid warming event on 2022-07-06 at 20:20-20:50 local time. Use moorings C2, C3 and C4.

What looks like a single rapid warming event in the figure above is in fact a rapid warm pulse associated with approx. 3 degrees of warming lasting less than 10 minutes between 20:25-20:35. This short pulse is followed by a more gradual and longer-lasting warming episode starting at around 20:37.

The central mooring (C3) appears to be somewhat protected from the warm water incursion during the first pulse of warming.

Figure
